---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../../data/site.js';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const href = (url) => {
  if (url.startsWith('http')) return url;
  const cleanBase = base.endsWith('/') ? base.slice(0, -1) : base;
  const cleanUrl = url.startsWith('/') ? url : `/${url}`;
  return `${cleanBase}${cleanUrl}`;
};

const title = "How to Delegate Without Micromanaging as a New Manager";
const description = "New managers either hoard work or hover. Learn a simple 4-step delegation method that builds trust and gets results.";
const topic = "Delegation";
const number = "02";
const longEmbed = "https://www.youtube.com/embed/oWsC7tHsI38";
const longWatch = "https://youtu.be/oWsC7tHsI38";
const shorts = [
  {
    "watch": "https://youtube.com/shorts/a6_tVVRPPvA",
    "embed": "https://www.youtube.com/embed/a6_tVVRPPvA"
  },
  {
    "watch": "https://youtube.com/shorts/wf8nNnS0d4M",
    "embed": "https://www.youtube.com/embed/wf8nNnS0d4M"
  },
  {
    "watch": "https://youtube.com/shorts/CJrRZKdNQ38",
    "embed": "https://www.youtube.com/embed/CJrRZKdNQ38"
  }
];
const related = [
  {
    "title": "Why New Managers Overexplain Under Pressure and How to Fix It",
    "slug": "/articles/why-new-managers-overexplain/",
    "topic": "Communication"
  },
  {
    "title": "Why First-Time Managers Struggle to Give Feedback and How to Fix It",
    "slug": "/articles/feedback-without-killing-morale/",
    "topic": "Feedback"
  }
];

const bookUrl = href('/books/the-first-30-days-as-a-new-manager/');
const articlesUrl = href('/articles/');
const resourcesUrl = href('/resources/');

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: title,
  description,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
  },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
    url: site.siteUrl,
  },
  mainEntityOfPage: new URL(`${base}articles/delegate-without-micromanaging/`, site.siteUrl).toString(),
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  path={`/articles/delegate-without-micromanaging/`}
  schema={[schema]}
>
  <main class="article-page">
    <nav class="crumbs">
      <a href={articlesUrl}>Articles</a>
      <span>/</span>
      <span>{number}</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="kicker">{topic}</p>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>{description}</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Read the book</a>
        <a href={resourcesUrl}>Resources</a>
        {longWatch && <a href={longWatch} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Watch video</a>}
      </div>
    </header>

    {longEmbed && (
      <section class="media-block">
        <div class="video-frame long">
          <iframe
            src={longEmbed}
            title={title}
            loading="lazy"
            allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen
          ></iframe>
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <article class="article-body">
      <h1>How to Delegate Without Micromanaging as a New Manager</h1>
<p>Most new managers don&#x27;t micromanage because they don&#x27;t trust their team.</p>
<p>They micromanage because they are still responsible for the work in their head.</p>
<p>You were promoted because you were good at doing the work. Now your job is to get the work done through other people. That transition feels like losing control. So you either do it yourself, or you hand it off and then hover.</p>
<p>Both fail.</p>
<h2>What usually happens</h2>
<p>It happens around week one or two. A task comes in. You know exactly how you would do it.</p>
<p>Option A: You keep it. “It’s faster if I just do it.” You end up working nights while your team is under-utilized.</p>
<p>Option B: You delegate it, but you check in three times a day. You rewrite their draft. You ask for updates that take longer to prepare than the task itself.</p>
<p>The team notices fast. Good people disengage when they feel watched. Slower people learn to wait for you to tell them what to do.</p>
<p>Delegation isn&#x27;t dumping work. And it isn&#x27;t supervising every step. It&#x27;s a clear handoff with a clear finish line.</p>
<h2>Why this becomes a problem</h2>
<p>Your capacity collapses. If you are still doing individual contributor work on top of managing, you will burn out by day 20. That is not sustainable.</p>
<p>The team never grows. If you rewrite everything, they never learn your standard. They learn to depend on your edits.</p>
<p>You become the bottleneck. Every decision routes through you. Work slows down, not because the team is slow, but because you are in the middle of everything.</p>
<p>Trust erodes both ways. You don&#x27;t trust them to deliver. They don&#x27;t trust you to let them deliver. That is how micromanagement starts, quietly.</p>
<h2>The mistake managers make</h2>
<p>The mistake is delegating tasks without delegating the outcome.</p>
<p>New managers say: “Can you work on this presentation?”</p>
<p>That is vague. No deadline, no standard, no scope. So two hours later you check in, because you are anxious. That check-in feels like micromanaging, because it is.</p>
<p>The problem is not your follow-up. The problem is your handoff was unclear.</p>
<h2>What to do instead</h2>
<p>Use Outcome, Constraints, Checkpoint, Don’t Hover.</p>
<p><strong>1. Outcome. One sentence.</strong> What does “done” look like? Be specific. Not “work on the report.” Say: “A one-page client summary with last month’s three key metrics, ready to send.”</p>
<p><strong>2. Constraints. Name the edges.</strong> Deadline. Format. Budget. Who needs to approve it. What NOT to do. Two or three constraints max. This prevents rework.</p>
<p><strong>3. Checkpoint. One scheduled check.</strong> Not random pings. Agree on one checkpoint before the deadline. “Send me a draft Thursday at 3pm, final is Friday.” This kills your urge to hover, because you know when you’ll see it.</p>
<p><strong>4. Don’t hover.</strong> Between handoff and checkpoint, leave them alone. If you think of something, write it down for the checkpoint. Do not Slack “just checking in!”. That is micromanaging.</p>
<p>If the result at the checkpoint is off, correct the outcome and constraints, not the person. Then give them the final run.</p>
<h2>Example</h2>
<p><strong>Instead of:</strong> “Hey, can you take the Q2 deck? Let me know if you need anything!” Then: 3 Slack pings, 2 “quick syncs”, and you rewriting half the slides the night before.</p>
<p><strong>Say:</strong> “Outcome: Update the Q2 client deck with the new numbers. 12 slides max, same template. Constraints: Deadline is Friday 2pm. Keep the executive summary to one slide. Checkpoint: Send me a draft Thursday 11am. I’ll give notes once. You own it from here.”</p>
<p>Then stop. Let Thursday come. Review once, clearly. Ship Friday.</p>
<p>That is delegation. Clear outcome, clear edge, one checkpoint, no hovering.</p>
<h2>How to apply this this week</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>List 3 tasks you are still doing yourself.</strong> Pick the lowest-risk one. Delegate it tomorrow using Outcome/Constraints/Checkpoint.</li>
<li><strong>Write the outcome sentence first.</strong> Before you assign anything, write “Done looks like…” in one sentence. If you can’t, you’re not ready to delegate it.</li>
<li><strong>Kill status pings.</strong> Replace all “how’s it going?” messages with one scheduled checkpoint. Put it in the calendar.</li>
<li><strong>Give notes once, in writing.</strong> At the checkpoint, give all feedback in one batch. No drip-feeding edits for two days.</li>
<li><strong>Don’t rewrite. Redirect.</strong> If the draft is 70% right, tell them exactly what to fix and let them fix it. Do not take the file and do it yourself. That teaches dependence.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Final note</h2>
<p>Delegation feels slow the first time. It is faster by the third time.</p>
<p>Your job in the first 30 days is not to prove you can still do the work. It is to prove the team can do the work without you hovering. That is how you build capacity.</p>
<p>Clear handoff. One checkpoint. No hovering. Repeat.</p>
<p>This article is based on the Plain Act approach to early management pressure.</p>
<p>---</p>
    </article>

    {shorts.length > 0 && (
      <section class="shorts-section">
        <p class="kicker">Shorts</p>
        <h2>Short clips from this lesson</h2>
        <div class="shorts-grid">
          {shorts.map((short, index) => (
            <div class="short-frame">
              <iframe
                src={short.embed}
                title={`${title} short ${index + 1}`}
                loading="lazy"
                allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
                allowfullscreen
              ></iframe>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <section class="cta-box">
      <p class="kicker">Plain Act</p>
      <h2>The First 30 Days as a New Manager</h2>
      <p>A practical manual for first-time managers carrying authority, feedback, delegation, and decision pressure.</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Open the book page</a>
        <a href={articlesUrl}>Back to articles</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="related">
      <p class="kicker">Related</p>
      <div class="related-grid">
        {related.map((item) => (
          <a class="related-card" href={href(item.slug)}>
            <span>{item.topic}</span>
            <strong>{item.title}</strong>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-page {
    max-width: 920px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2.6rem 1.2rem 4rem;
  }

  .crumbs {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.45rem;
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .crumbs a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .article-hero {
    max-width: 780px;
  }

  .kicker {
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .article-hero h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(2.1rem, 5vw, 4.4rem);
    line-height: 0.96;
    letter-spacing: -0.06em;
  }

  .article-hero p {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 1.06rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  .hero-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    margin-top: 1.2rem;
  }

  .hero-actions a {
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 999px;
    padding: 0.55rem 0.82rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.035);
  }

  .media-block {
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .video-frame {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    background: #05070a;
    box-shadow: 0 24px 70px rgba(0,0,0,.2);
  }

  .video-frame.long {
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
  }

  .video-frame iframe,
  .short-frame iframe {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    border: 0;
  }

  .article-body {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    padding: 1.2rem 0;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(h1) {
    display: none;
  }

  .article-body :global(h2) {
    margin-top: 2.1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    font-size: clamp(1.35rem, 2.5vw, 2rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.035em;
  }

  .article-body :global(h3) {
    margin-top: 1.6rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(p),
  .article-body :global(li) {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.78;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(strong) {
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(blockquote) {
    margin: 1.2rem 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    color: var(--text);
    border-radius: .75rem;
  }

  .shorts-section,
  .cta-box,
  .related {
    margin-top: 2.2rem;
  }

  .shorts-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .short-frame {
    position: relative;
    aspect-ratio: 9 / 16;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: .9rem;
    background: #05070a;
  }

  .cta-box {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1.2rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    padding: 1.2rem;
  }

  .cta-box h2 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 3vw, 2.4rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
  }

  .cta-box p {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .related-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .related-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: .45rem;
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
  }

  .related-card span {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: .75rem;
    letter-spacing: .12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .shorts-grid,
    .related-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
